        <div id="tab1" class="tab-content active" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-tab1">
            <h2>⚖️ Environmental Legislation & Permitting Framework</h2>
            
            <div class="legislation-panel">
                <h3><i class="fas fa-gavel"></i> Understanding 'Take' Under Tasmanian Law</h3>
                <p>Under Tasmanian legislation, the term <strong>'take'</strong> is used to identify activities which are prohibited without authorisation:</p>
                <ul style="margin-left:1.5rem; margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
                    <li>For species listed on the <strong>Threatened Species Protection Act 1995</strong>, 'take' includes killing, catching, damaging or collecting any listed plant, plant part or product – including seed, foliage, roots, bark, sap etc.</li>
                    <li>For any flora species on land reserved under the <strong>Nature Conservation Act 2002</strong>, 'take' includes destroying, damaging or interfering with a native plant, plant part or product, including dead plant products such as wood, leaf litter etc.</li>
                </ul>
                <p><cite>Source: <a href="https://nre.tas.gov.au/conservation/forms-and-permits/scientific-permits-and-authorities-to-collect-native-flora" target="_blank">NRE Tas Scientific Permits</a></cite></p>
            </div>

            <h3>📋 When is a Permit Required?</h3>
            <div class="card-deck">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
                    <h4>Threatened Species</h4>
                    <p>Native plant species listed as <strong>endangered, vulnerable or rare</strong> under the <em>Threatened Species Protection Act 1995</em>. In this case, a permit is required <strong>regardless of the land tenure</strong> (public or private land).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-tree"></i>
                    <h4>Public Lands</h4>
                    <p>Any native plant species from <strong>public lands managed by the State Government</strong> (National Parks, State Forest, Crown Land, reserves) requires a permit.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-hand-holding-heart"></i>
                    <h4>Private Sanctuaries</h4>
                    <p>Any native plant species from <strong>Private Sanctuaries and Private Nature Reserves</strong> declared under the <em>Nature Conservation Act 2002</em>, if you are <strong>not the owner</strong> of that land.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>🔍 How to Apply for a Permit</h3>
            <div style="background:#f5f9f5; border-radius:1.5rem; padding:1.5rem;">
                <ol style="margin-left:1.5rem;">
                    <li><strong>Determine if you need a permit</strong> using the criteria above.</li>
                    <li><strong>Read the Permit Application Guidelines</strong> – includes information on how to apply, fill out forms, and what happens after submission.</li>
                    <li><strong>Complete the Permit Application Form</strong> (Word or PDF format) available from NRE Tas.</li>
                    <li>Submit to the appropriate section:
                        <ul style="margin-left:1.5rem;">
                            <li><strong>For Non-Threatened Plants from Reserved Lands:</strong> Ecologist, Natural Values Science, Natural and Cultural Heritage Division, GPO Box 44 Hobart, TAS 7001</li>
                            <li><strong>For Threatened Native Plants:</strong> Threatened Species, Natural and Cultural Heritage Division, GPO Box 44 Hobart, TAS 7001</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <p><strong>Contact:</strong> Flora Permit Enquiries – <a href="mailto:FloraPermit.Enquiries@nre.tas.gov.au">FloraPermit.Enquiries@nre.tas.gov.au</a></p>
            </div>

            <h3>⚠️ Important Considerations</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Increment cores and wood samples</strong> on reserved land for dendrochronology research have additional restrictions – contact FloraPermit.Enquiries@nre.tas.gov.au</li>
                <li><strong>Aboriginal and Historic heritage</strong> must be considered before any ground disturbing works. Failure to demonstrate due diligence may result in substantial penalties. See Aboriginal Heritage Tasmania or Heritage Tasmania.</li>
                <li><strong>Commonwealth areas in Tasmania:</strong> For permits covering Commonwealth land, see the Commonwealth Government Department of Environment and Heritage website for Listed Species Permits.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>📚 Key Legislation Summary</h3>
            <div class="act-list">
                <div class="act-item"><i class="fas fa-file-contract"></i> <strong>Threatened Species Protection Act 1995</strong> (Tas) – listed species, any tenure</div>
                <div class="act-item"><i class="fas fa-file-contract"></i> <strong>Nature Conservation Act 2002</strong> (Tas) – reserved land, sanctuaries</div>
                <div class="act-item"><i class="fas fa-file-contract"></i> <strong>National Parks and Reserves Management Act 2002</strong> – public reserves</div>
                <div class="act-item"><i class="fas fa-file-contract"></i> <strong>Crown Lands Act 1976</strong> – Crown land</div>
                <div class="act-item"><i class="fas fa-file-contract"></i> <strong>EPBC Act 1999</strong> (Commonwealth) – Matters of National Environmental Significance</div>
            </div>
