            <h3>Provenance: The Science of Local Adaptation</h3>
            <div style="background:#fff2db; border-radius:2rem; padding:2rem; margin:2rem 0;">
                <h4>Why Provenance Matters</h4>
                <p>Plants collected from similar environmental conditions (rainfall, temperature, soil type, altitude) will have adapted to those conditions. Using local provenance seed increases survival rates in restoration projects by up to 300% (Florabank data).</p>
                <p><strong>Seed Transfer Zones:</strong> Many states have defined zones – collect within the same zone as planting site. In Tasmania, consider bioregions (e.g., Furneaux, Ben Lomond, West Coast).</p>
                <p><strong>Climate matching:</strong> With climate change, some practitioners use 'climate-adjusted provenancing' – collecting from slightly warmer/drier areas to future-proof restoration.</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Uncertain Species Protocol</h3>
            <div style="background:#dff0df; border-radius:2rem; padding:2rem;">
                <h4>Step-by-Step Voucher Collection</h4>
                <ol>
                    <li>Collect representative specimen: 30cm branch with leaves, flowers if possible, fruits (if available)</li>
                    <li>Press immediately in newspaper with cardboard, change papers daily for 2 weeks</li>
                    <li>Photograph: whole plant, bark, leaves (upper and lower), flower close-up, fruit, habitat</li>
                    <li>Record: location (GPS GDA2020), date, habitat, plant height, flower colour, abundance, associated species</li>
                    <li>Assign temporary ID (e.g., "Acacia sp. Freer Farm")</li>
                    <li>Submit to state herbarium for identification (may take weeks, fee applicable – contact herbarium first)</li>
