            <h2>🪴 Collection Methods & Equipment</h2>
            
            <h3>Manual Collection Techniques</h3>
            <table class="tool-matrix">
                <tr><th>Method</th><th>Description</th><th>Suitable Species</th><th>Equipment</th></tr>
                <tr><td>Hand picking</td><td>Selectively remove ripe fruits by hand</td><td>Fleshy fruits (Billardiera, Coprosma), large pods (Acacia)</td><td>Bags, buckets, secateurs, gloves</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Stripping</td><td>Run hand along stem to strip seeds</td><td>Grasses, sedges (Poa, Carex, Juncus)</td><td>Gloves, collection bag, sieve for cleaning</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Cutting branches</td><td>Remove branches with seed, place on tarp</td><td>Eucalypts, Banksia, Melaleuca, Leptospermum</td><td>Pole pruner, secateurs, loppers, tarp (3x3m)</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Shaking/beating</td><td>Shake or beat branches over sheet to release seed</td><td>Dehiscent species (Leptospermum, Melaleuca, Callistemon)</td><td>Sticks, hessian, tarpaulin, collection trays</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Vacuum collection</td><td>Modified leaf blower/vac to suck seeds from plants/ground</td><td>Small-seeded species (Callistemon, Melaleuca, Ericaceae)</td><td>Blower-vac with collection bag, fine mesh filters</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Fallen material</td><td>Collect freshly fallen seed from ground under parent plants</td><td>Banksia cones, eucalypt fruit, Allocasuarina cones</td><td>Hand rakes, bags, sieves for cleaning</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Rifle/bow (specialist)</td><td>Shoot small branches to bring down high seed</td><td>Tall eucalypts, rainforest trees</td><td>Firearms licence, landholder permission, safety training</td></tr>
            </table>

            <h3>Above 2m Collection Methods</h3>
            <div class="card-deck">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-arrow-up"></i>
                    <h4>Pole Pruner + Ground Sheet</h4>
                    <p>Extendable pruner (3-8m). Cut branches over tarp. Best for most species up to 8m. Requires practice to avoid branch damage. Ensure tarp is securely pegged in wind.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-ladder"></i>
                    <h4>Ladders & Ropes</h4>
                    <p>Orchard ladder (tripod) or climbing ropes with harness (requires certified training). Use for tall trees up to 15m. Ensure 3 points of contact, ladder on firm ground, spotter present.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-bullseye"></i>
                    <h4>Hydraulic Lift/Elevated Work Platform</h4>
                    <p>For large-scale commercial collection. Requires operator licence, traffic management if near roads. Expensive but efficient for high-volume collection.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Equipment Care & Maintenance</h3>
            <ul style="margin-left:2rem;">
                <li><strong>Secateurs/loppers:</strong> Sharpen with diamond file after each trip, clean with 70% methylated spirits (biosecurity), oil pivot points with light machine oil</li>
                <li><strong>Pole pruner:</strong> Check rope condition (fraying), blade sharpness, extension locks functional. Clean after each use.</li>
                <li><strong>Tarpaulins:</strong> Shake out debris, dry thoroughly before storing, repair tears with tape or stitching</li>
                <li><strong>Bags:</strong> Paper bags – single use only; hessian – wash in hot water and dry; plastic – wash with detergent, dry, check for holes</li>
                <li><strong>Scales:</strong> Calibrate annually with test weights, check battery before each trip, zero before weighing</li>
                <li><strong>GPS:</strong> Update maps, carry spare batteries (2 sets), download waypoints before trip</li>
                <li><strong>Seed sieves:</strong> Clean with brush, check for bent mesh, store flat</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Collection Quantity Calculations</h3>
            <div style="background:#f5f9f5; border-radius:2rem; padding:2rem;">
                <h4>How Much to Collect?</h4>
                <p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> collect 2-3 times the amount needed, accounting for:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Cleaning losses (chaff, empty seeds, debris) – can be 30-80% depending on species</li>
                    <li>Viability testing failures (germination tests may show 20-90% viability)</li>
                    <li>Storage/insurance buffer (10-20% extra for backup)</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Example calculation:</strong> Need 1000 viable seeds for nursery. Estimated cleaning loss 40%, viability 60% → collect approx 2,800 seeds (1000 / 0.6 / 0.6).</p>
                <p><strong>Weight estimation:</strong> Count seeds in 1g sample × total grams collected. e.g., Eucalyptus 500 seeds/g → 50g = 25,000 seeds.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

