        <div id="tab5" class="tab-content">
            <!-- (content unchanged) -->
            <h2>♻️ Sustainable Collection Practices</h2>
            
            <h3>The 20% Rule: Scientific Basis</h3>
            <div style="background:#eef5ee; border-radius:2rem; padding:2rem;">
                <p>Research (Florabank, 2021) shows collecting <strong>no more than 20% of available seed</strong> from a population ensures:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Sufficient seed for natural regeneration and recruitment</li>
                    <li>Maintenance of genetic diversity within the population</li>
                    <li>Food source for native animals (birds, mammals, insects) preserved</li>
                    <li>Population resilience to environmental stress</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Application:</strong> Visually estimate total seed crop (e.g., count fruits on representative branches, multiply by number of branches). Collect ≤20% from each plant. For small populations (<20 plants), collect from fewer plants (e.g., 5 plants) or lower percentage (10%).</p>
            </div>

            <h3>Ethical Collection Guidelines</h3>
            <div class="card-deck">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-fire"></i>
                    <h4>Avoid Post-Fire Areas</h4>
                    <p>Plants regenerating after fire need all seeds for population recovery. Wait at least 2-3 years post-fire, and only collect if population is robust (>50 plants).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-paw"></i>
                    <h4>Protect Fauna</h4>
                    <p>Check for nests, hollows, feeding activity before collecting. Delay collection if birds are nesting in target plants. Leave seed on ground for ground-foraging birds and mammals. Avoid collecting from plants with active insect herbivory (may indicate stressed plants).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-biohazard"></i>
                    <h4>Biosecurity Protocols</h4>
                    <p>Clean footwear, tools, vehicle tyres before entering and after leaving site. Use 70% ethanol or 1% bleach solution (30min contact). Prevents spread of Phytophthora cinnamomi (root rot), myrtle rust (Austropuccinia psidii), and weed seeds.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3>Environmental Impact Assessment (Template)</h3>
            <div class="checklist-super">
                <h4>Pre-Collection Environmental Checklist</h4>
                <div class="checklist-grid">
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Check for threatened flora populations (consult EPBC Protected Matters Search Tool, Tasmanian TSP listings)</div>
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Identify and mark sensitive habitats (wetlands, moss beds, rock outcrops, threatened vegetation communities)</div>
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Plan access routes to minimise trampling and soil disturbance</div>
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Check for weed infestations – plan to clean down after leaving weedy areas</div>
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Assess soil erosion risk – avoid steep slopes when wet, use designated tracks</div>
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Check weather forecast – avoid collection before rain (mould risk), postpone if high winds (safety)</div>
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Plan to leave site cleaner than found (remove rubbish, flagging tape, food scraps)</div>
                    <div class="checklist-item"><input type="checkbox"> Record any environmental observations (wildlife sightings, weed presence, fire damage)</div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

