            <h2>🧹 Seed Cleaning & Storage Protocols</h2>
            
            <h3>Cleaning Methods by Fruit Type</h3>
            <table class="tool-matrix">
                <tr><th>Fruit Type</th><th>Cleaning Method</th><th>Equipment</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
                <tr><td>Fleshy (A)</td><td>Macerate (mush) fruit, ferment 1-3 days, float off pulp, rinse seeds, dry</td><td>Bowl, sieve (graded), water, food processor (gentle pulse), paper towel</td><td>Remove all flesh to prevent mould; change water daily; some seeds need acid treatment</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Dry Dehiscent (B)</td><td>Thresh (rub) to break open capsules, sieve to separate, winnow (air)</td><td>Rubber mat, sieves (various mesh sizes), seed blower, wind tray, leaf blower</td><td>Eucalypts: oven at 50-70°C for 24h to open capsules</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Dry Indehiscent (C)</td><td>Rub over coarse sieve, air separation, gravity table</td><td>Graded sieves (2-5mm), seed blower, gravity separator</td><td>Grasses – remove awns, chaff; use pneumatic separator if available</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Cone-bearing (Banksia, Hakea)</td><td>Oven heating to open woody cones, then shake out seeds</td><td>Oven (50-70°C), trays, heat-proof containers, tweezers</td><td>Monitor temperature closely – don't cook seeds; check regularly</td></tr>
                <tr><td>Legumes (Acacia, Pultenaea)</td><td>Thresh pods, sieve, sometimes heat treatment for hard seeds</td><td>Threshing bag, sieves, hot water (optional)</td><td>Some need boiling water or scarification for germination – not for storage</td></tr>
            </table>

            <h3>Drying Protocols</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Air drying:</strong> Spread in single layer on newspaper/trays, room temperature (15-25°C), low humidity (<50%), good airflow. Turn daily for even drying.</li>
                <li><strong>Silica gel drying:</strong> For humid conditions, use sealed container with colour-indicating silica gel (ratio 1:1 seed:gel). Regenerate gel in oven when saturated.</li>
                <li><strong>Moisture content target:</strong> Orthodox seeds 5-8% for long-term storage (can be tested with moisture meter). Recalcitrant seeds cannot be dried below 30-50% – sow fresh.</li>
                <li><strong>Testing dryness:</strong> Seed should crack/snap cleanly when bent, not feel soft or cool to touch.</li>
                <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Drying typically 1-4 weeks depending on seed size and humidity.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Storage Systems</h3>
            <div class="card-deck">
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-thermometer-half"></i>
                    <h4>Short-term (0-2 years)</h4>
                    <p>Airtight containers (glass jars with rubber seal, ziplock bags with air expelled), cool dark cupboard (15-20°C constant). Add silica gel packets (change monthly). Check monthly for mould, insects, condensation.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-snowflake"></i>
                    <h4>Long-term (2-20+ years)</h4>
                    <p>Dried seeds (5-8% moisture) in sealed foil packets or glass jars, freezer (-18°C) or fridge (4°C). Use moisture-proof containers. Thaw to room temperature before opening (prevents condensation). Ideal for seed banking.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="info-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-exclamation-triangle"></i>
                    <h4>Recalcitrant Seeds</h4>
                    <p>Cannot be stored long-term. Sow fresh, or store moist (not wet) with fungicide in fridge (4°C) for weeks-months (e.g., rainforest species like Nothofagus, Elaeocarpus). Check regularly for mould/germination.</p>
                </div>
            </div>

