<div id="tab12" class="tab-content" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="tab-tab12">
    <h2><i class="fas fa-book-open"></i> Interactive Glossary</h2>
    <p>Hover over any <span class="glossary-term">highlighted term<span class="glossary-definition">Terms like this one will show a definition when you hover.</span></span> to see its definition. Terms are organised by category for easy reference.</p>
    
    <div style="background:var(--bg-light); border-radius:1.5rem; padding:1.5rem; margin:2rem 0;">
        <h3>🌱 Seed Biology & Structure</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Cotyledon<span class="glossary-definition">The embryonic first leaves of a seed; they store food (in dicots) or absorb endosperm (in monocots). Number of cotyledons distinguishes monocots (1) from dicots (2).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Radicle<span class="glossary-definition">The embryonic root that emerges first during germination; develops into the primary root system.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Plumule<span class="glossary-definition">The embryonic shoot (stem and first true leaves) above the cotyledons.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Endosperm<span class="glossary-definition">Nutritive tissue inside seeds that provides energy for germination; may be absorbed by cotyledons before germination (in some species).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Hilum<span class="glossary-definition">The scar on the seed coat where it was attached to the ovary wall; often visible as a distinct mark or colour change.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Micropyle<span class="glossary-definition">A tiny opening in the seed coat through which water enters to initiate germination; originally the site of pollen tube entry.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Testa<span class="glossary-definition">The hard outer seed coat that protects the embryo; may be thin (e.g., Acacia) or thick and woody (e.g., Banksia).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Aril<span class="glossary-definition">A fleshy, often brightly coloured structure attached to the seed; attracts birds for dispersal (e.g., native currant).</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>💧 Seed Storage Behaviour</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Orthodox seed<span class="glossary-definition">Seeds that can be dried to low moisture content (5-8%) and frozen for long-term storage. Most Australian native seeds are orthodox (e.g., Eucalyptus, Acacia).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Recalcitrant seed<span class="glossary-definition">Seeds that cannot be dried or frozen; they remain high in moisture (30-70%) and must be sown fresh or stored short-term in moist conditions. Examples: rainforest species like Nothofagus, Elaeocarpus, Araucaria.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Intermediate seed<span class="glossary-definition">Seeds with storage behaviour between orthodox and recalcitrant; can tolerate some drying but not freezing. May survive 1-5 years in cool, dry conditions.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Desiccation tolerance<span class="glossary-definition">A seed's ability to survive extreme drying without losing viability; orthodox seeds have high desiccation tolerance.</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>⏰ Dormancy & Germination</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Dormancy<span class="glossary-definition">A state in which viable seeds fail to germinate even under favourable conditions; an evolutionary adaptation to survive adverse periods.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Physical dormancy<span class="glossary-definition">Seed coat is impermeable to water; requires scarification (scratching, hot water, fire) to break dormancy. Common in Fabaceae (pea family).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Physiological dormancy<span class="glossary-definition">Internal chemical inhibitors prevent germination; requires stratification (cold or warm treatment) to break. Common in many temperate species.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Morphological dormancy<span class="glossary-definition">Embryo is underdeveloped at seed dispersal and needs time to grow inside the seed before germination can occur.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Stratification<span class="glossary-definition">Cold treatment (usually 1-3 months at 2-5°C) to break physiological dormancy; mimics winter conditions. Also called cold stratification.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Warm stratification<span class="glossary-definition">Exposure to warm temperatures (20-30°C) to break dormancy in some species; often followed by cold stratification for double dormancy.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Scarification<span class="glossary-definition">Any treatment that breaks or weakens the seed coat to allow water imbibition. Methods include mechanical (nicking, sandpaper), thermal (hot water, fire), or chemical (acid).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Vernalization<span class="glossary-definition">Cold treatment applied to imbibed seeds or seedlings to induce flowering in biennial plants; different from stratification which promotes germination.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">After-ripening<span class="glossary-definition">A period of dry storage at room temperature that allows seeds to overcome dormancy; required for many grass species and Asteraceae.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Smoke germination<span class="glossary-definition">Germination triggered by smoke or smoke-water chemicals (karrikins); essential for many Australian fire-adapted species (e.g., Stylidium, Actinotus).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Heat shock<span class="glossary-definition">Brief exposure to high temperatures (40-100°C) that breaks physical dormancy in hard-seeded species; mimics soil heating during fire.</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>🌿 Fruit & Seed Dispersal</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Dehiscent<span class="glossary-definition">Seed pods or capsules that open naturally when ripe to release seeds. Common in Type B fruits (Acacia, Eucalyptus, pea family).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Indehiscent<span class="glossary-definition">Fruits that do not open to release seeds; seeds are dispersed while still inside the fruit. Common in Type C fruits (grasses, sedges, daisy family).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Serotinous<span class="glossary-definition">Capsules or cones that require heat (typically from bushfire) to open and release seeds. Seeds are held in woody fruits for years until fire triggers release. Examples: Banksia, Hakea, some Eucalypts.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Pyriscence<span class="glossary-definition">The scientific term for fire-triggered seed release; from Greek 'pyr' (fire). Often confused with serotiny.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Myrmecochory<span class="glossary-definition">Seed dispersal by ants. Seeds have elaiosomes (fatty appendages) that attract ants; ants carry seeds to nests, eat elaiosome, and discard viable seed. Common in Acacia, Pultenaea.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Elaiosome<span class="glossary-definition">A fleshy, lipid-rich structure attached to seeds that attracts ants; removed by ants without damaging the seed. Also called an ant attractant.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Ornithochory<span class="glossary-definition">Seed dispersal by birds; typically involves fleshy fruits (Type A) with colourful arils or pulp. Birds eat fruit and pass viable seeds.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Anemochory<span class="glossary-definition">Wind dispersal; seeds often have wings (e.g., Eucalyptus), plumes (e.g., Clematis), or are tiny dust seeds (e.g., orchids).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Hydrochory<span class="glossary-definition">Water dispersal; seeds float and are carried by water currents. Common in riparian and coastal species (e.g., mangroves, Melaleuca).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Synaptospermy<span class="glossary-definition">Dispersal of multiple seeds together as a unit (e.g., whole grass spikelet).</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>📊 Seed Quality & Testing</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Viability<span class="glossary-definition">The percentage of seeds in a lot that are alive and capable of germinating under suitable conditions. Tested via cut test, tetrazolium (TZ) test, or germination trial.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Tetrazolium test (TZ)<span class="glossary-definition">A biochemical viability test using colourless tetrazolium salt; living embryos turn red, dead tissue remains unstained. Results in 24-48 hours.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Cut test<span class="glossary-definition">Quick field method to estimate viability: cut seeds open and inspect embryos. Firm, white/cream embryos indicate viable; soft, discoloured, or shrivelled indicate non-viable.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Float test<span class="glossary-definition">Seeds placed in water; viable seeds often sink, non-viable float. Not reliable for all species (some viable seeds float due to air spaces).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Germination test<span class="glossary-definition">Controlled germination trial under optimal conditions (light, temperature, moisture). Most accurate but slow (weeks to months).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Purity<span class="glossary-definition">Percentage of pure seed (by weight) in a seed lot, excluding chaff, soil, inert matter, and other species.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Moisture content<span class="glossary-definition">Amount of water in seeds, expressed as percentage of fresh weight or dry weight. Critical for determining storage method.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Thousand seed weight (TSW)<span class="glossary-definition">Weight of 1000 seeds; used to estimate seed quantity, compare seed size between lots/species.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Seed lot<span class="glossary-definition">A collection of seeds of a single species collected from the same location, same date, same population.</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>🧬 Genetics & Provenance</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Provenance<span class="glossary-definition">The original geographic source or environment of a seed lot; critical for restoration success. Using local provenance seed increases survival rates by up to 300%.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Local provenance<span class="glossary-definition">Seed collected from the same or similar environmental conditions (rainfall, soil, altitude) as the planting site.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Climate-adjusted provenancing<span class="glossary-definition">Modern approach collecting from slightly warmer/drier areas to future-proof restoration against climate change.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Seed transfer zone<span class="glossary-definition">Geographic area within which seed can be moved with minimal risk of maladaptation; based on climate, soil, and bioregions.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Population bottleneck<span class="glossary-definition">Reduction in genetic diversity when too few parent plants are sampled; avoid by collecting from 20-50 plants.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Inbreeding depression<span class="glossary-definition">Reduced fitness in offspring due to mating between related individuals; risk increases if seed collected from too few plants.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Genetic drift<span class="glossary-definition">Random changes in gene frequencies in small populations; collecting from small populations can capture these random variations.</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>📝 Collection & Field Terms</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Phenology<span class="glossary-definition">The study of cyclic and seasonal natural phenomena, especially in relation to climate and plant life. Critical for timing seed collection.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Maturation date<span class="glossary-definition">The date when seeds reach physiological maturity and are ready for collection; varies by species, altitude, seasonal conditions.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Seed crop<span class="glossary-definition">The total amount of seed produced by a population in a given season; varies annually (mast seeding years vs. low years).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Mast seeding<span class="glossary-definition">Synchronous, highly variable seed production across years; some years have massive seed crops, others very little. Common in Eucalyptus, Nothofagus.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Voucher specimen<span class="glossary-definition">Pressed plant sample with flowers/fruits deposited in a herbarium to verify species identification. Essential for uncertain species.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Flagging tape<span class="glossary-definition">Coloured tape (biodegradable preferred) used to mark collection plants for later return; remove after collection.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Thresh<span class="glossary-definition">The process of beating or rubbing dried fruits to separate seeds from pods/capsules.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Winnow<span class="glossary-definition">Using air flow to separate lighter chaff from heavier seeds; can be done with wind, fans, or seed blowers.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Dieback<span class="glossary-definition">Disease causing plant decline and death; Phytophthora cinnamomi (root rot) is a major threat in Australian ecosystems.</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>⚖️ Legal & Conservation Terms</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Take (legal)<span class="glossary-definition">Under Tasmanian legislation, includes collecting, damaging, destroying, or interfering with native plants or plant parts on reserved land or for threatened species.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Threatened species<span class="glossary-definition">Plant or animal species listed as endangered, vulnerable, or rare under state or Commonwealth legislation. Collection requires a permit regardless of land tenure.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Endangered<span class="glossary-definition">Species facing a very high risk of extinction in the wild in the near future.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Vulnerable<span class="glossary-definition">Species facing a high risk of extinction in the wild in the medium-term future.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Rare<span class="glossary-definition">Species with small populations that are not currently endangered or vulnerable but are at risk.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">EPBC Act<span class="glossary-definition">Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 (Commonwealth); Australia's key environmental legislation covering Matters of National Environmental Significance.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Biosecurity<span class="glossary-definition">Practices to prevent the spread of pests and diseases between sites – includes cleaning tools, footwear, and vehicles with 70% ethanol or 1% bleach.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Phytophthora<span class="glossary-definition">Phytophthora cinnamomi – a deadly soil-borne pathogen (root rot) that kills many native plants. Spread by soil movement; requires strict hygiene protocols.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Myrtle rust<span class="glossary-definition">Austropuccinia psidii – a fungal disease affecting Myrtaceae family (eucalypts, melaleucas, leptospermum). Reportable disease.</span></span>
        </p>

        <h3>🏞️ Habitat & Ecological Terms</h3>
        <p>
            <span class="glossary-term">Riparian<span class="glossary-definition">Relating to wetlands, riverbanks, and streamside vegetation; often has different collection and access restrictions.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Sclerophyll<span class="glossary-definition">Vegetation with hard, leathery leaves adapted to dry conditions; includes dry sclerophyll (open forest) and wet sclerophyll (tall open forest).</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Heathland<span class="glossary-definition">Vegetation dominated by small-leaved shrubs on nutrient-poor soils; often rich in biodiversity.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Ecotone<span class="glossary-definition">Transition zone between two vegetation communities; often has high species diversity.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Remnant vegetation<span class="glossary-definition">Native vegetation remaining after clearing; often isolated patches in agricultural or urban landscapes.</span></span> · 
            <span class="glossary-term">Corridor<span class="glossary-definition">Strips of native vegetation connecting larger habitat areas; critical for wildlife movement and gene flow.</span></span>
        </p>
    </div>

    <h3>📚 Complete A–Z Glossary</h3>
    <table class="tool-matrix">
        <tr><th style="width:200px;">Term</th><th>Definition</th></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>After-ripening</strong></td><td>A period of dry storage at room temperature that allows seeds to overcome dormancy; required for many grass species and Asteraceae.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Anemochory</strong></td><td>Wind dispersal; seeds often have wings (e.g., Eucalyptus), plumes (e.g., Clematis), or are tiny dust seeds (e.g., orchids).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Aril</strong></td><td>A fleshy, often brightly coloured structure attached to the seed; attracts birds for dispersal (e.g., native currant, billardiera).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Biosecurity</strong></td><td>Practices to prevent the spread of pests and diseases between sites – includes cleaning tools, footwear, and vehicles with 70% ethanol or 1% bleach. Critical for preventing Phytophthora spread.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Climate-adjusted provenancing</strong></td><td>Modern approach collecting from slightly warmer/drier areas to future-proof restoration against climate change.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Cotyledon</strong></td><td>The embryonic first leaves of a seed; they store food (in dicots) or absorb endosperm (in monocots). Number distinguishes monocots (1) from dicots (2).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Cut test</strong></td><td>Quick field method to estimate viability: cut seeds open and inspect embryos. Firm, white/cream embryos indicate viable; soft, discoloured, or shrivelled indicate non-viable.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Dehiscent</strong></td><td>Seed pods or capsules that open naturally when ripe to release seeds. Common in Type B fruits (Acacia, Eucalyptus, pea family).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Desiccation tolerance</strong></td><td>A seed's ability to survive extreme drying without losing viability; orthodox seeds have high desiccation tolerance.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Dieback</strong></td><td>Disease causing plant decline and death; Phytophthora cinnamomi (root rot) is a major threat in Australian ecosystems.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Dormancy</strong></td><td>A state in which viable seeds fail to germinate even under favourable conditions; an evolutionary adaptation to survive adverse periods.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Ecotone</strong></td><td>Transition zone between two vegetation communities; often has high species diversity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Elaiosome</strong></td><td>A fleshy, lipid-rich structure attached to seeds that attracts ants; removed by ants without damaging the seed. Also called an ant attractant.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Endangered</strong></td><td>Species facing a very high risk of extinction in the wild in the near future under state or Commonwealth legislation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Endosperm</strong></td><td>Nutritive tissue inside seeds that provides energy for germination; may be absorbed by cotyledons before germination (in some species).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>EPBC Act</strong></td><td>Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999 (Commonwealth); Australia's key environmental legislation covering Matters of National Environmental Significance.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Flagging tape</strong></td><td>Coloured tape (biodegradable preferred) used to mark collection plants for later return; remove after collection.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Float test</strong></td><td>Seeds placed in water; viable seeds often sink, non-viable float. Not reliable for all species (some viable seeds float due to air spaces).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Genetic drift</strong></td><td>Random changes in gene frequencies in small populations; collecting from small populations can capture these random variations.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Germination test</strong></td><td>Controlled germination trial under optimal conditions (light, temperature, moisture). Most accurate but slow (weeks to months).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Heat shock</strong></td><td>Brief exposure to high temperatures (40-100°C) that breaks physical dormancy in hard-seeded species; mimics soil heating during fire.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Heathland</strong></td><td>Vegetation dominated by small-leaved shrubs on nutrient-poor soils; often rich in biodiversity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Hilum</strong></td><td>The scar on the seed coat where it was attached to the ovary wall; often visible as a distinct mark or colour change.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Hydrochory</strong></td><td>Water dispersal; seeds float and are carried by water currents. Common in riparian and coastal species (e.g., mangroves, Melaleuca).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Inbreeding depression</strong></td><td>Reduced fitness in offspring due to mating between related individuals; risk increases if seed collected from too few plants.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Indehiscent</strong></td><td>Fruits that do not open to release seeds; seeds are dispersed while still inside the fruit. Common in Type C fruits (grasses, sedges, daisy family).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Intermediate seed</strong></td><td>Seeds with storage behaviour between orthodox and recalcitrant; can tolerate some drying but not freezing. May survive 1-5 years in cool, dry conditions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Local provenance</strong></td><td>Seed collected from the same or similar environmental conditions (rainfall, soil, altitude) as the planting site.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Mast seeding</strong></td><td>Synchronous, highly variable seed production across years; some years have massive seed crops, others very little. Common in Eucalyptus, Nothofagus.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Maturation date</strong></td><td>The date when seeds reach physiological maturity and are ready for collection; varies by species, altitude, seasonal conditions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Micropyle</strong></td><td>A tiny opening in the seed coat through which water enters to initiate germination; originally the site of pollen tube entry.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Moisture content</strong></td><td>Amount of water in seeds, expressed as percentage of fresh weight or dry weight. Critical for determining storage method.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Morphological dormancy</strong></td><td>Embryo is underdeveloped at seed dispersal and needs time to grow inside the seed before germination can occur.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Myrmecochory</strong></td><td>Seed dispersal by ants. Seeds have elaiosomes (fatty appendages) that attract ants; ants carry seeds to nests, eat elaiosome, and discard viable seed.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Myrtle rust</strong></td><td>Austropuccinia psidii – a fungal disease affecting Myrtaceae family (eucalypts, melaleucas, leptospermum). Reportable disease.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Ornithochory</strong></td><td>Seed dispersal by birds; typically involves fleshy fruits (Type A) with colourful arils or pulp. Birds eat fruit and pass viable seeds.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Orthodox seed</strong></td><td>Seeds that can be dried to low moisture content (5-8%) and frozen for long-term storage. Most Australian native seeds are orthodox (e.g., Eucalyptus, Acacia).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Phenology</strong></td><td>The study of cyclic and seasonal natural phenomena, especially in relation to climate and plant life. Critical for timing seed collection.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Physical dormancy</strong></td><td>Seed coat is impermeable to water; requires scarification (scratching, hot water, fire) to break dormancy. Common in Fabaceae (pea family).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Physiological dormancy</strong></td><td>Internal chemical inhibitors prevent germination; requires stratification (cold or warm treatment) to break. Common in many temperate species.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Phytophthora</strong></td><td>Phytophthora cinnamomi – a deadly soil-borne pathogen (root rot) that kills many native plants. Spread by soil movement; requires strict hygiene protocols.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Plumule</strong></td><td>The embryonic shoot (stem and first true leaves) above the cotyledons.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Population bottleneck</strong></td><td>Reduction in genetic diversity when too few parent plants are sampled; avoid by collecting from 20-50 plants.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Provenance</strong></td><td>The original geographic source or environment of a seed lot; critical for restoration success. Using local provenance seed increases survival rates by up to 300%.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Purity</strong></td><td>Percentage of pure seed (by weight) in a seed lot, excluding chaff, soil, inert matter, and other species.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Pyriscence</strong></td><td>The scientific term for fire-triggered seed release; from Greek 'pyr' (fire). Often confused with serotiny.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Radicle</strong></td><td>The embryonic root that emerges first during germination; develops into the primary root system.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Rare</strong></td><td>Species with small populations that are not currently endangered or vulnerable but are at risk under state legislation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Recalcitrant seed</strong></td><td>Seeds that cannot be dried or frozen; they remain high in moisture (30-70%) and must be sown fresh or stored short-term in moist conditions. Examples: rainforest species like Nothofagus, Elaeocarpus.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Remnant vegetation</strong></td><td>Native vegetation remaining after clearing; often isolated patches in agricultural or urban landscapes.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Riparian</strong></td><td>Relating to wetlands, riverbanks, and streamside vegetation; often has different collection and access restrictions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Scarification</strong></td><td>Any treatment that breaks or weakens the seed coat to allow water imbibition. Methods include mechanical (nicking, sandpaper), thermal (hot water, fire), or chemical (acid).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Sclerophyll</strong></td><td>Vegetation with hard, leathery leaves adapted to dry conditions; includes dry sclerophyll (open forest) and wet sclerophyll (tall open forest).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Seed crop</strong></td><td>The total amount of seed produced by a population in a given season; varies annually (mast seeding years vs. low years).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Seed lot</strong></td><td>A collection of seeds of a single species collected from the same location, same date, same population.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Seed transfer zone</strong></td><td>Geographic area within which seed can be moved with minimal risk of maladaptation; based on climate, soil, and bioregions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Serotinous</strong></td><td>Capsules or cones that require heat (typically from bushfire) to open and release seeds. Seeds are held in woody fruits for years until fire triggers release. Examples: Banksia, Hakea, some Eucalypts.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Smoke germination</strong></td><td>Germination triggered by smoke or smoke-water chemicals (karrikins); essential for many Australian fire-adapted species (e.g., Stylidium, Actinotus).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Stratification</strong></td><td>Cold treatment (usually 1-3 months at 2-5°C) to break physiological dormancy; mimics winter conditions. Also called cold stratification.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Synaptospermy</strong></td><td>Dispersal of multiple seeds together as a unit (e.g., whole grass spikelet).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Take (legal)</strong></td><td>Under Tasmanian legislation, includes collecting, damaging, destroying, or interfering with native plants or plant parts on reserved land or for threatened species.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Testa</strong></td><td>The hard outer seed coat that protects the embryo; may be thin (e.g., Acacia) or thick and woody (e.g., Banksia).</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Tetrazolium test (TZ)</strong></td><td>A biochemical viability test using colourless tetrazolium salt; living embryos turn red, dead tissue remains unstained. Results in 24-48 hours.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Thousand seed weight (TSW)</strong></td><td>Weight of 1000 seeds; used to estimate seed quantity, compare seed size between lots/species.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Threatened species</strong></td><td>Plant or animal species listed as endangered, vulnerable, or rare under state or Commonwealth legislation. Collection requires a permit regardless of land tenure.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Thresh</strong></td><td>The process of beating or rubbing dried fruits to separate seeds from pods/capsules.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Vernalization</strong></td><td>Cold treatment applied to imbibed seeds or seedlings to induce flowering in biennial plants; different from stratification which promotes germination.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Viability</strong></td><td>The percentage of seeds in a lot that are alive and capable of germinating under suitable conditions. Tested via cut test, tetrazolium (TZ) test, or germination trial.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Voucher specimen</strong></td><td>Pressed plant sample with flowers/fruits deposited in a herbarium to verify species identification. Essential for uncertain species.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Vulnerable</strong></td><td>Species facing a high risk of extinction in the wild in the medium-term future under state or Commonwealth legislation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Warm stratification</strong></td><td>Exposure to warm temperatures (20-30°C) to break dormancy in some species; often followed by cold stratification for double dormancy.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Winnow</strong></td><td>Using air flow to separate lighter chaff from heavier seeds; can be done with wind, fans, or seed blowers.</td></tr>
    </table>
    
